  section 4 Typography
    section 4.1 Type Scale
    The M3 type scale provides a range of sizes to support different needs. It usesRobotoas the default font (or system fonts on specific platforms).
  section 5 Layout
    section 5.1 8dp Grid
    All components and layout elements should align to an8dp square grid. For smaller elements like icons and type, a 4dp grid can be used.
    section 5.2 Spacing
    Spacing between elements should be in increments of 4dp or 8dp (e.g., 8dp, 16dp, 24dp, 32dp).
    section 5.3 Window Size Classes
  section 6 Components
    section 6.1 Action
      - Buttons:Corner radius is typically20dp(fully rounded for small buttons). High-emphasis buttons use the Primary color.
      - FAB:Corner radius is12dpfor small/standard FABs and28dpfor large FABs.
      - Chips:Used for input, selection, filtering, or triggering actions. Types include assist, filter, input, and suggestion.
    section 6.2 Containment
      - Cards:Corner radius is12dp. Left/right padding is16dp. Types include Elevated, Filled, and Outlined.
      - Dialogs:Corner radius is28dp. Padding is 24dp.
      - Bottom Sheets:Anchored to the bottom of the screen; used for secondary or modal content.
    section 6.3 Communication
      - Badges:Display notifications, counts, or status on icons. Content is limited to 4 characters.
    section 6.4 Navigation
      - Navigation Bar:For primary destinations on compact/medium screens.
      - Navigation Drawer:For larger screens (expanded/large/extra-large); being replaced by expanded navigation rails.
      - Tabs:Organize content across different screens or views; primary for main destinations, secondary for related content.
    section 6.5 Information
      - Lists:Help users find and act on items; should be short, scannable, and logically ordered.
      - Menus:Present a temporary set of actions relative to a component or field.
  section 6 Writing
    section 6.1 Voice and Tone
      - Direct:Use clear and concise language.
      - Helpful:Provide useful information to guide the user.
      - Human:Use a friendly and professional tone.
    section 6.2 Capitalization
    UseSentence casefor most UI text, including titles, labels, and buttons. Title Case should be avoided unless it's a brand name.